<question-stem>
<para> How does the professor characterize the spoken language children use
before they enter school?<mediaExhibit frameType="mp3" mediaRef="toeflPrac10232.mp3"/></para>
</question-stem>
<answer-choice-set>
<answer-choice> As primarily short sentences using simple words and phrases</answer-choice>
<answer-choice> As more advanced than the language they use in reading and
writing</answer-choice>
<answer-choice correct="yes"> As centered on contexts involving "here" and
"now"</answer-choice>
<answer-choice> As grammatically inaccurate most of the time</answer-choice>
</answer-choice-set>
<explanation interaction="true">
<para> The professor states that the conversations of pre-schoolers are <emphasis
emphasis-type="italic"> usually about </emphasis>things and people "here"
and "now," so (C) is correct. (A) is incorrect because the professor states
that written sentences are longer (than spoken sentences), but she doesn't
limit this characteristic to pre-schoolers. (B) is false, and while she states
that, in general, there are grammatical errors in spoken language, she does
not state that pre-school children make mistakes in their language use "most
of the time," so (D) is not correct.</para>
</explanation>
</question>
